exactly who he is.

1141
01:09:08,896 --> 01:09:12,717
We did some additional photography
in this scene

1142
01:09:12,817 --> 01:09:17,304
and it was to exploit
one of the qualities in Loki

1143
01:09:17,404 --> 01:09:19,932
that we felt we could,

1144
01:09:20,032 --> 01:09:22,852
by virtue of how good
Tom Hiddleston's performance was,

1145
01:09:22,952 --> 01:09:25,980
also include, aside from him
being a genuine brother,

1146
01:09:26,080 --> 01:09:29,650
and being a hurt brother

1147
01:09:29,750 --> 01:09:32,920
and an ambitious
and perhaps rather jealous brother,

1148
01:09:33,754 --> 01:09:37,283
to be mischievous and dangerous
is a necessity for Loki.

1149
01:09:37,383 --> 01:09:42,621
Even if one does not necessarily
suggest that he is preternaturally evil,

1150
01:09:42,721 --> 01:09:47,251
but that his capacity for wrongdoing
is emerging, forming,

1151
01:09:47,351 --> 01:09:49,336
shaping itself before our very eyes.

1152
01:09:49,436 --> 01:09:53,174
This scene allows us
to see a more calculating Loki at work.

1153
01:09:53,274 --> 01:09:55,134
Someone who is playing the poker game

1154
01:09:55,234 --> 01:09:58,053
with another master player,
his real father,

1155
01:09:58,153 --> 01:10:02,224
but his real father does not,
at this point, know that this is his son.

1156
01:10:02,324 --> 01:10:05,311
He was abandoned, after all,
and he would have assumed,

1157
01:10:05,411 --> 01:10:08,063
and another version of this scene
suggested this,

1158
01:10:08,163 --> 01:10:12,459
that Odin would have killed
that bastard child of yesteryear.

1159
01:10:12,877 --> 01:10:15,362
So, this becomes a scene
of many levels

1160
01:10:15,462 --> 01:10:18,699
between two very calculating,
dangerous guys

1161
01:10:18,799 --> 01:10:20,951
who are used
to the world of brinkmanship,

1162
01:10:21,051 --> 01:10:23,137
and two good poker faces.

1163
01:10:25,055 --> 01:10:28,417
We return to Heimdall's observatory

1164
01:10:28,517 --> 01:10:32,213
where again, you, in this scene,
get to enjoy

1165
01:10:32,313 --> 01:10:34,715
the power of Idris Elba's performance.

1166
01:10:34,815 --> 01:10:36,111
First of all, the look is fantastic.

1167
01:10:36,191 --> 01:10:40,471
I can't imagine another actor who would
carry off this incredible costume,

1168
01:10:40,571 --> 01:10:44,058
which Alex Byrne, I think,
has triumphantly presented

1169
01:10:44,158 --> 01:10:47,102
as the kind of look that a guardian,

1170
01:10:47,202 --> 01:10:49,939
a man who really is the person
who says,

1171
01:10:50,039 --> 01:10:53,000
and we believe him,
"Thou shalt not pass."

1172
01:10:53,792 --> 01:10:58,489
In wonderful, wonderful golds
and with a great shape, great design,

1173
01:10:58,589 --> 01:11:00,699
it's a marvellous frame for an actor.

1174
01:11:00,799 --> 01:11:05,079
And in it, you have Idris Elba,
whose voice we slightly amend

1175
01:11:05,179 --> 01:11:11,352
to just maximise the beautiful, rich,
dark, warm tones in it,

1176
01:11:11,560 --> 01:11:16,006
because, as the single
representative of Asgard out there,

1177
01:11:16,106 --> 01:11:18,926
we wanted, every time we heard
and saw him,

1178
01:11:19,026 --> 01:11:23,013
to be aware of this
memory of the guardian,

1179
01:11:23,113 --> 01:11:26,700
the man whom you disobey at your peril.

1180
01:11:27,117 --> 01:11:28,435
It's nice to go from him

1181
01:11:28,535 --> 01:11:32,539
to something as relatively mundane
as Jane's caravan.

1182
01:11:33,207 --> 01:11:35,943
This is the moment in the movie,

1183
01:11:36,043 --> 01:11:39,380
in a way, where it could go
several different places.

1184
01:11:40,714 --> 01:11:43,909
Thor is without his powers,
he's starting, he's reborn, if you like,

1185
01:11:44,009 --> 01:11:48,455
and so, this is a moment
where we understand,

1186
01:11:48,555 --> 01:11:52,835
maybe with Loki's activities
in the worlds above,

1187
01:11:52,935 --> 01:11:55,379
that it's the calm before the storm.

1188
01:11:55,479 --> 01:11:59,633
But it's the calm in which the audience
have a chance to take in this new Thor,

1189
01:11:59,733 --> 01:12:02,194
and, I think, fully invest in him

1190
01:12:03,278 --> 01:12:05,598
and perhaps invest in the idea

1191
01:12:05,698 --> 01:12:08,142
of some kind of relationship
between him and Jane.

1192
01:12:08,242 --> 01:12:11,186
It is difficult in a big action film

1193
01:12:11,286 --> 01:12:15,791
to allow the room for romance,
if you like, or a kind of

1194
01:12:17,418 --> 01:12:21,755
chemistry between
perhaps the central boy and gal,

1195
01:12:22,923 --> 01:12:26,744
having any extra dimensions,

1196
01:12:26,844 --> 01:12:28,996
or even just having
a feeling of authenticity

1197
01:12:29,096 --> 01:12:30,998
to whatever level that's pursued.

1198
01:12:31,098 --> 01:12:35,002
It isn't the case that these things
have to be grand passions.

1199
01:12:35,102 --> 01:12:37,107
I suppose what you want to feel
is that they like each other,

1200
01:12:37,187 --> 01:12:39,340
that they get on, that they're listening,

1201
01:12:39,440 --> 01:12:42,176
that it's a relationship in which, slowly,

1202
01:12:42,276 --> 01:12:44,261
you're interested in what happens,

1203
01:12:44,361 --> 01:12:46,347
and in which you might invest.

1204
01:12:46,447 --> 01:12:47,723
It can't be overburdened

1205
01:12:47,823 --> 01:12:52,603
by suddenly becoming
the grand passion of the ages,

1206
01:12:52,703 --> 01:12:56,649
and yet, there is much to value

1207
01:12:56,749 --> 01:13:00,335
out of these instant connections

1208
01:13:00,627 --> 01:13:02,696
between, in this case,
people from other worlds.

1209
01:13:02,796 --> 01:13:05,427
Many people have asked me about the
sort of Shakespearean influence on this.

1210
01:13:05,507 --> 01:13:09,203
And I can't say any of it was remotely,
if it is, there,

1211
01:13:09,303 --> 01:13:10,996
that it's only because
Shakespeare nicked

1212
01:13:11,096 --> 01:13:16,168
some terrific story ideas and plot points
from great writers of the past,

1213
01:13:16,268 --> 01:13:17,836
and we continue to steal from him.

1214
01:13:17,936 --> 01:13:22,883
And one situation
that clearly was a big hit for him

1215
01:13:22,983 --> 01:13:26,053
was the idea of putting people together
from different worlds,

1216
01:13:26,153 --> 01:13:28,597
the <i>Romeo and Juliet,</i>
if you like, of it all.

1217
01:13:28,697 --> 01:13:31,642
And so, the beginnings of that
starts here,

1218
01:13:31,742 --> 01:13:35,604
which is simply that a new and humble
and modest Thor is listening,

1219
01:13:35,704 --> 01:13:39,316
and is asking questions
and is caring about someone else.

1220
01:13:39,416 --> 01:13:42,069
He is interested in someone else.

1221
01:13:42,169 --> 01:13:47,533
And that generosity of spirit, of course,
is incredibly winning for us, for Jane,

1222
01:13:47,633 --> 01:13:51,829
and you see a quite honest
beginning to a relationship

1223
01:13:51,929 --> 01:13:55,582
that leaves the question mark
of exactly how far can it go

1224
01:13:55,682 --> 01:13:58,185
during the context of this story?

1225
01:13:59,144 --> 01:14:01,463
And what kind of weight can it hold,

1226
01:14:01,563 --> 01:14:06,819
and can it do that
whilst still allowing for it to be fun?

1227
01:14:07,319 --> 01:14:09,847
And I think that many people have
commented about this scene,

1228
01:14:09,947 --> 01:14:11,974
that it's their favourite scene
in the movie.

1229
01:14:12,074 --> 01:14:18,288
You get some wonderful simple things,
which are, this look, for instance.

1230
01:14:18,705 --> 01:14:21,416
Natalie Portman looking at someone

1231
01:14:22,084 --> 01:14:25,279
and letting us understand
that she may feel something for him

1232
01:14:25,379 --> 01:14:28,090
that is even beginning to surprise her.

1233
01:14:28,715 --> 01:14:31,827
I think that that qualify
in her performance,

1234
01:14:31,927 --> 01:14:34,496
subtle, brief, rich,

1235
01:14:34,596 --> 01:14:39,685
is one of the things
that sort of helps distinguish the picture

1236
01:14:40,394 --> 01:14:43,464
in terms of how it
approaches certain things.

1237
01:14:43,564 --> 01:14:46,425
We're trying not to work too hard,
but just for it to be real,

1238
01:14:46,525 --> 01:14:49,762
and I think that she's very real,
very convincing there,

1239
01:14:49,862 --> 01:14:51,513
she's very, very charming

1240
01:14:51,613 --> 01:14:54,700
as she laughs
about the Hubble/Hooble mix-up.

1241
01:15:20,100 --> 01:15:22,211
This is a handsome shot of our hero.

1242
01:15:22,311 --> 01:15:25,547
All the way through shooting,
between Mr. Hemsworth, Ms. Portman,

1243
01:15:25,647 --> 01:15:29,776
and all of them,
Kat, Jaimie, all the boys,

1244
01:15:30,569 --> 01:15:32,930
Tom and then some
of the other Warriors Three,

1245
01:15:33,030 --> 01:15:34,451
who I'll talk about in a little while,

1246
01:15:34,531 --> 01:15:35,766
one was constantly reminded

1247
01:15:35,866 --> 01:15:38,869
of what an amazingly handsome
group of people,

1248
01:15:39,703 --> 01:15:41,021
marvellous to look at.

1249
01:15:41,121 --> 01:15:47,169
Here, the Warriors Three
are disputing what to do.

1250
01:15:48,170 --> 01:15:49,571
Josh Dallas plays Fandral,

1251
01:15:49,671 --> 01:15:53,467
and he does so with an English accent
with great aplomb,

1252
01:15:53,800 --> 01:15:56,078
marvellous debonair dash.

1253
01:15:56,178 --> 01:15:58,872
And he's matched equally
by the tremendous Ray Stevenson,

1254
01:15:58,972 --> 01:16:04,169
who you'll know from his brilliant turn
on the HBO TV series <i>Rome</i>

1255
01:16:04,269 --> 01:16:05,587
and many, many other films.

1256
01:16:05,687 --> 01:16:08,006
I worked with Ray many moons ago,

1257
01:16:08,106 --> 01:16:13,470
and it was a pleasure to bring
his incredible screen gifts.

1258
01:16:13,570 --> 01:16:15,931
He's got such a great face for movies.

1259
01:16:16,031 --> 01:16:18,308
Handsome lad
who knows how to be still.

1260
01:16:18,408 --> 01:16:22,229
He's matched here by Tadanobu Asano,
a great star from Japan,

1261
01:16:22,329 --> 01:16:26,733
who brings to the role of
Hogun the Grim inscrutability,

1262
01:16:26,833 --> 01:16:30,487
but an enigmatic, playful intelligence

1263
01:16:30,587 --> 01:16:34,074
and a sort of deadly capacity
for physical violence.

1264
01:16:34,174 --> 01:16:36,827
You know that when he speaks,
it's gonna be important.

1265
01:16:36,927 --> 01:16:39,997
There was great camaraderie
between these four,

1266
01:16:40,097 --> 01:16:43,750
and it really fuelled
the quality of the scenes,

1267
01:16:43,850 --> 01:16:47,854
the sense of that bond between them,
and loyalty and fun, of course.

1268
01:16:55,696 --> 01:17:00,184
It's true to say that there was more of
the Warriors Three and Lady Sif shot,

1269
01:17:00,284 --> 01:17:02,978
and once again, not through
lack of qualify from them,

1270
01:17:03,078 --> 01:17:09,943
but through a simple
traffic jam of elements

1271
01:17:10,043 --> 01:17:15,007
that we wanted to put gracefully
into this world of the film,

1272
01:17:16,466 --> 01:17:18,096
it wasn't possible to include everything.

1273
01:17:18,176 --> 01:17:20,120
But they had great fun.

1274
01:17:20,220 --> 01:17:23,457
And some of it now
infuses this part of the movie

1275
01:17:23,557 --> 01:17:28,228
where once again, we enjoy
the fact of the gods coming to Earth.

1276
01:17:31,815 --> 01:17:35,302
Here, the rhythm of the film,
as it switches so instantaneously,

1277
01:17:35,402 --> 01:17:39,723
is a great tribute
to the gifts of our editor, Paul Rubell,

1278
01:17:39,823 --> 01:17:42,017
who was a wonderful collaborator
throughout.

1279
01:17:42,117 --> 01:17:47,898
A marvellous and award-winning editor,
and very musical.

1280
01:17:47,998 --> 01:17:51,735
I always think it's very helpful
if an editor is musical.

1281
01:17:51,835 --> 01:17:55,447
He plays the piano,
but he has an intuitive feel

1282
01:17:55,547 --> 01:17:59,201
for the length of a cut
and the feel of a cut,

1283
01:17:59,301 --> 01:18:01,370
and has so many tricks at his disposal

1284
01:18:01,470 --> 01:18:03,705
to do with being able
to use everything we can.

1285
01:18:03,805 --> 01:18:07,751
Whether it's split screens,
or accelerating shots,

1286
01:18:07,851 --> 01:18:09,753
or flipping and flopping shots,

1287
01:18:09,853 --> 01:18:12,172
really, we used
every kind of trick in the book here,

1288
01:18:12,272 --> 01:18:16,343
and he had that in addition to the
great treasure trove of visual effects

1289
01:18:16,443 --> 01:18:19,237
that produces things like the Destroyer.

1290
01:18:22,741 --> 01:18:25,452
So, we bring the Warriors Four to Earth.

1291
01:18:26,745 --> 01:18:31,733
This is a fun moment
and one that is tough to get just right.

1292
01:18:31,833 --> 01:18:35,879
It's very nicely underpinned
by Patrick's music.

1293
01:18:36,338 --> 01:18:38,907
There's a part of the magic of movies,

1294
01:18:39,007 --> 01:18:41,910
the character Volstagg
was not in the shot that you saw,

1295
01:18:42,010 --> 01:18:44,474
we filmed him separately afterwards,
and we put him into the shot.

1296
01:18:44,554 --> 01:18:47,082
The kind of thing
that seemed necessary in post,

1297
01:18:47,182 --> 01:18:50,585
and only possible because you're
working on a great, big Marvel movie

1298
01:18:50,685 --> 01:18:52,629
where that kind of thing can happen.

1299
01:18:52,729 --> 01:18:54,881
It was one of the numerous moments
where I thought,

1300
01:18:54,981 --> 01:18:57,884
"Gosh, if I had this opportunity
on previous films,"

1301
01:18:57,984 --> 01:19:00,262
"they'd all have
cost squinty billion dollars."

1302
01:19:00,362 --> 01:19:02,931
But I hasten to add
that's not what this cost,

1303
01:19:03,031 --> 01:19:07,994
but it does provide
the chance to get things right.

1304
01:19:10,414 --> 01:19:14,735
Just before we head
into the last phase of the movie,

1305
01:19:14,835 --> 01:19:17,112
which is full of action and destruction,

1306
01:19:17,212 --> 01:19:20,407
it's lovely to have had,
including the cup drop,

1307
01:19:20,507 --> 01:19:24,261
a piece of delicious daft comedy.

1308
01:19:25,011 --> 01:19:29,291
Before now, coming back to
the big question of why they're here,

1309
01:19:29,391 --> 01:19:32,185
of taking Thor home.

1310
01:19:39,943 --> 01:19:42,012
But of course,
it being the kind of movie it is,

1311
01:19:42,112 --> 01:19:43,533
we're not going to make it
as easy as that,

1312
01:19:43,613 --> 01:19:47,225
and there's going to be
a significant sequence now

1313
01:19:47,325 --> 01:19:51,271
where the Destroyer, called by Loki,
comes to Earth

1314
01:19:51,371 --> 01:19:54,483
to deal with Thor and prevent his return.

1315
01:19:54,583 --> 01:19:57,402
First, of course,
Loki has to deal with Heimdall,

1316
01:19:57,502 --> 01:19:59,237
who's been registering suspicion.

1317
01:19:59,337 --> 01:20:01,239
And I love, by the way, this shot

1318
01:20:01,339 --> 01:20:04,368
and the way it evokes the kinds of work

1319
01:20:04,468 --> 01:20:08,430
that were done
by the French VFX vendors BUF,

1320
01:20:08,847 --> 01:20:11,333
Pierre Buffin and his team
with Nicolas Chevallier,

1321
01:20:11,433 --> 01:20:13,960
a great team there
who were able to give us

1322
01:20:14,060 --> 01:20:16,963
both the incredible water effects

1323
01:20:17,063 --> 01:20:23,053
and the beaten copper,
space-aged qualities

1324
01:20:23,153 --> 01:20:25,389
to the outside of the observatory.

1325
01:20:25,489 --> 01:20:28,183
This marvellous effect with Heimdall

1326
01:20:28,283 --> 01:20:32,270
and the freezing that comes out
of the Casket of Ancient Winters.

1327
01:20:32,370 --> 01:20:34,167
I love the water
in the background of this shot

1328
01:20:34,247 --> 01:20:37,167
and the idea
of encasing Heimdall like this.

1329
01:20:45,258 --> 01:20:47,285
Back on Earth,
we had other things to contend with.

1330
01:20:47,385 --> 01:20:50,080
In New Mexico,
quite splendid though it is,

1331
01:20:50,180 --> 01:20:51,790
and although some of this is enhanced,

1332
01:20:51,890 --> 01:20:53,583
we had our own challenges
with the weather.

1333
01:20:53,683 --> 01:20:58,255
Not with the arrival of the Destroyer,
but with four seasons in a day,

1334
01:20:58,355 --> 01:21:01,675
sometimes 50-mile-an-hour winds,

1335
01:21:01,775 --> 01:21:06,112
sometimes hail, sometimes snow,
sometimes rain,

1336
01:21:06,863 --> 01:21:08,014
literally all in one day.

1337
01:21:08,114 --> 01:21:10,308
And so, sometimes working out quite
what we could shoot

1338
01:21:10,408 --> 01:21:13,995
or if we could still shoot
was pretty difficult.

1339
01:21:16,122 --> 01:21:18,400
Once again, Darcy, it seems to me,

1340
01:21:18,500 --> 01:21:20,444
is a great representative
of the audience,

1341
01:21:20,544 --> 01:21:23,196
and Kat Dennings played her beautifully.

1342
01:21:23,296 --> 01:21:28,869
She has a great comic gift
and is also extremely smart.

1343
01:21:28,969 --> 01:21:32,372
She's one of those characters
who allows you to believe

1344
01:21:32,472 --> 01:21:36,643
that there is a very different
kind of individual in there,

1345
01:21:37,143 --> 01:21:39,880
beyond the surface
of a very quick-witted,

1346
01:21:39,980 --> 01:21:43,525
sort of cynical, sarcastic individual.

1347
01:21:43,817 --> 01:21:48,889
And it seems to me she scores
in almost every moment she speaks,

1348
01:21:48,989 --> 01:21:50,991
and it's very valuable.

1349
01:21:55,287 --> 01:21:58,190
What it gives you, as you approach
these big sequences

1350
01:21:58,290 --> 01:22:00,253
at the end of the movie,
is a chance to orchestrate.

1351
01:22:00,333 --> 01:22:04,738
You know that somewhere
you want to go from fun to laughter,

1352
01:22:04,838 --> 01:22:08,408
to thrill, to exhilaration, to violence,

1353
01:22:08,508 --> 01:22:14,289
to big music, to little music,
to rhythm, to excitement,

1354
01:22:14,389 --> 01:22:20,253
and so, there's this thriller throb
to some of the action here.

1355
01:22:20,353 --> 01:22:22,756
Camera moving all of the time,

1356
01:22:22,856 --> 01:22:26,401
interrupted by this,
the great weight of the Destroyer.

1357
01:22:27,193 --> 01:22:28,261
In planning this sequence,

1358
01:22:28,361 --> 01:22:31,326
I remember it was one of the first things
I did when I arrived in New Mexico,

1359
01:22:31,406 --> 01:22:32,599
and down this very street,

1360
01:22:32,699 --> 01:22:36,077
where the beautiful Jaimie Alexander
is just about to hide herself,

